---
import Explorable from "../layouts/Explorable.astro";
import { href } from "../lib/href";
import { neighbors } from "../lib/phase1";

const { prev, next } = neighbors("agent-loop");

const scenes = [
  {
    id: "intro",
    eyebrow: "Start here",
    title: "A model, on its own, only writes text.",
    body: "Claude is a model: it takes in words and predicts words back. That is the whole of what it does by itself. It can tell you how to fix your code, but it cannot open a file, run a command, or see whether it was right. For any of that, it needs a program around it.",
  },
  {
    id: "harness",
    eyebrow: "The harness",
    title: "Claude Code is the program around the model.",
    body: "It is a piece of software the model can send instructions to: open this file, change this line, run this command. The harness carries out the action on your computer and hands the result back. The model decides what to do; the harness does it and reports what happened. That program is the harness.",
  },
  {
    id: "loop",
    eyebrow: "The loop",
    title: "Together they work in a loop.",
    body: "The model and the harness go around the same small loop: read to understand the task, plan the steps, act on one of them, check the result. If there is more to do, they go around again. Everything Claude Code does is this loop, repeated. Here the task is a real one. Add a dark-mode button, and watch the loop turn.",
  },
  {
    id: "read",
    eyebrow: "Read",
    title: "Reading the project is itself tool calls.",
    body: "Before it can do anything, the model needs to see your files. It can't read them on its own, so it asks the harness to open one. Here that's “Read index.html.” That request is a tool call: the harness opens the file and hands back what's inside. Gathering context is a series of these calls, not a single free step.",
  },
  {
    id: "plan",
    eyebrow: "Plan",
    title: "Then it breaks the goal into steps.",
    body: "Now that it has read the page, the model writes a short plan: add the button, add the dark-mode styles, make the button switch them. This part is just the model thinking. No tool runs and nothing on your computer changes yet. It is only deciding what to do, and in what order.",
  },
  {
    id: "act",
    eyebrow: "Act",
    title: "It changes one file with a tool.",
    body: "Now it does the first step. The model asks the harness to edit the file, “Edit index.html,” with the exact change to make. The harness makes the edit and confirms it. Acting is the one kind of step that actually changes something on your computer, and it, too, is a tool call.",
  },
  {
    id: "check",
    eyebrow: "Check",
    title: "It looks at the result, then goes again.",
    body: "With one step done, the model takes stock: the button is in, but two steps are left. So it loops back to the top and starts the next one. Read, plan, act, check. Around and around, one step per pass, until the plan is finished and the task is actually done.",
  },
  {
    id: "play",
    eyebrow: "Your turn",
    title: "Step through the loop yourself.",
    body: "Press Step to move the loop one stage at a time and watch it build the dark-mode button across three passes. Read and Act each run a tool; Plan and Check are the model thinking, with no tool. Press Reset to start over.",
  },
];
---

<Explorable
  title="The agent loop · Lesson 1 · Harness Atlas"
  description="A model alone only writes text. Claude Code is the harness around it, a program the model tells to read files, change them, and run commands. Together they work in a loop: read, plan, act, check, until the task is done."
  backHref={href("phase-1")}
  backLabel="Lesson 1"
  tag="Part 01 · The agent loop"
  eyebrow="The agent loop"
  h1="How Claude Code turns a request into work."
  lede="A model on its own only writes text. Claude Code is the harness around it: a program the model can tell to open files, change them, and run commands on your computer. The two work in a loop. The model reads the project, plans, acts, then checks the result, and that loop is what turns a plain request into finished work."
  canvasId="al-canvas"
  canvasAria="A four-stage loop drawn as a ring: Read at the top, Plan at the right, Act at the bottom, Check at the left, with clockwise arrows. Read and Act show the harness running a tool; Plan and Check are the model thinking, with no tool."
  legend={[
    { accent: "context", label: "Read" },
    { accent: "purple", label: "Plan" },
    { accent: "action", label: "Act" },
    { accent: "verified", label: "Check" },
  ]}
  outroEyebrow="What you just saw"
  outroTitle="That loop is all of Claude Code."
  outroBody="Every task runs through the same four stages: read, plan, act, and check, repeated until the work is done. The model decides what to do; the harness reads the files, makes the changes, and reports back, one tool call at a time. The rest of Lesson 1 zooms in on the parts of this loop, starting with the tool calls themselves."
  prev={prev}
  next={next}
  fallbackHref="phase-1"
  fallbackLabel="Back to Lesson 1"
>
  {
    scenes.map((s) => (
      <article class="scene" data-scene={s.id}>
        <p class="scene-eyebrow">{s.eyebrow}</p>
        <h2>{s.title}</h2>
        <p>{s.body}</p>
        {s.id === "play" && (
          <div class="controls">
            <button class="ctl" id="al-step" type="button">
              Step →
            </button>
            <button class="ctl" id="al-reset" type="button">
              Reset
            </button>
          </div>
        )}
      </article>
    ))
  }
</Explorable>
<script>
  import { initAgentLoop } from "../scripts/agentLoop";
  initAgentLoop();
</script>
